SIMPLE: emu
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emu
<hw>E"mu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Pg. <ets>ema</ets>
ostrich, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧mou</ets>, <ets>⟦eacute⟧meu</ets>, emu.]</ety>
<fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld> <def>A large Australian bird, of two species
(<spn>Dromaius Nov⟦ae⟧-Hollandi⟦ae⟧</spn> and <spn>D. irroratus</spn>),
related to the cassowary and the ostrich. The emu runs swiftly, but is
unable to fly.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>emeu</asp> and
<asp>emew</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name is sometimes erroneously applied, by the
Brazilians, to the rhea, or South American ostrich.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Emu wren</b></col>. <cd>See in the
Vocabulary.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emulable</ent>⟦br⟧
